Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:02.92,Default,,0,0,0,,This case is all about {\i1}Megalosaurus{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.92,0:00:05.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a giant, 9-meter long lizard
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.40,0:00:09.36,Default,,0,0,0,,That roamed around Oxfordshire around about a hundred and sixty million years ago
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.36,0:00:11.36,Default,,0,0,0,,But how do we know this? I mean, even I'm not that old!
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.74,0:00:18.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, this was first found by William Buckland, who was a geologist in the 19th century.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.42,0:00:20.72,Default,,0,0,0,,He quickly realised what he had
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.72,0:00:25.90,Default,,0,0,0,,but also there were no 9-metre long carnivorous lizards wandering around Oxfordshire
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.90,0:00:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,So, he reasoned that at some time in the past, they must have been here but had gone extinct.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.66,0:00:34.42,Default,,0,0,0,,As other bones were discovered, all around the country and all around the planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.42,0:00:37.24,Default,,0,0,0,,The name 'Dinosaur' was thought up to describe them
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.24,0:00:41.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here in this case, we have the first described bones of any dinosaur
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.92,0:00:47.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and they show how much our wildlife, and our planet, has changed through its long history
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.22,0:00:49.22,Default,,0,0,0,,
